stories.description:
Create a new SWR hook for fetching discovery collections from the backend API.

Create file: `src/hooks/useDiscoveryCollections.ts`

The hook should:
1. Fetch from GET /discovery/collections using the existing `api.get()` from api-client.ts
2. Use SWR with a 5-minute deduplication interval (collections change rarely)
3. Return: collections array, isLoading, isError, mutate

Also add TypeScript types to `src/types/api.ts`:
```typescript
// Discovery Collections
export interface CollectionStock {
  ticker: string;
  name: string;
  exchange: string;
  sector: string;
  market_cap: number | null;
  price: number | null;
  price_change: number | null;
  vetr_score: number | null;
}

export interface DiscoveryCollection {
  id: string;
  name: string;
  tagline: string;
  icon: string;
  criteria_summary: string;
  stocks: CollectionStock[];
}

export interface DiscoveryCollectionsData {
  collections: DiscoveryCollection[];
}
```

The hook pattern should follow the existing useStocks.ts pattern:
- Uses `api.get<ApiResponse<DiscoveryCollectionsData>>()` for type-safe fetching
- Returns `{ collections, isLoading, isError, mutate }`
- Handles API errors gracefully

IMPORTANT: The /discovery/collections endpoint uses JWT auth (not admin secret). The existing api-client.ts already adds JWT Bearer token automatically to all requests, so this will work out of the box.

Must pass `npm run build`.

Add the API endpoint and data models for fetching discovery collections.

1. Add DTOs in `app/src/main/java/com/vettr/android/core/data/remote/DiscoveryCollectionDto.kt`:
```kotlin
package com.vettr.android.core.data.remote

import com.google.gson.annotations.SerializedName

data class DiscoveryCollectionsResponse(
    @SerializedName("success") val success: Boolean,
    @SerializedName("data") val data: DiscoveryCollectionsData
)

data class DiscoveryCollectionsData(
    @SerializedName("collections") val collections: List<DiscoveryCollectionDto>
)

data class DiscoveryCollectionDto(
    @SerializedName("id") val id: String,
    @SerializedName("name") val name: String,
    @SerializedName("tagline") val tagline: String,
    @SerializedName("icon") val icon: String,
    @SerializedName("criteria_summary") val criteriaSummary: String,
    @SerializedName("stocks") val stocks: List<CollectionStockDto>
)

data class CollectionStockDto(
    @SerializedName("ticker") val ticker: String,
    @SerializedName("name") val name: String,
    @SerializedName("exchange") val exchange: String,
    @SerializedName("sector") val sector: String,
    @SerializedName("market_cap") val marketCap: Double?,
    @SerializedName("price") val price: Double?,
    @SerializedName("price_change") val priceChange: Double?,
    @SerializedName("vetr_score") val vetrScore: Int?
)
```

2. Add endpoint to VettrApi.kt:
```kotlin
@GET("discovery/collections")
suspend fun getDiscoveryCollections(
    @Header("X-Admin-Secret") adminSecret: String = ADMIN_SECRET
): DiscoveryCollectionsResponse
```

Note: The endpoint actually uses JWT auth, but since the Android app currently uses admin secret for all calls, we'll use admin secret here too. The backend accepts both.

Wait ‚Äî actually check if the backend discovery route accepts admin secret. If not, the admin secret header will just be ignored and auth will fail. Let me check... The discovery endpoint uses `authMiddleware` (JWT only, not admin). So we need to use the JWT Bearer token instead.

Actually, looking at the existing Android code, ALL endpoints use X-Admin-Secret. The auth interceptor also adds Bearer token. So both headers are sent. But the discovery endpoint only accepts JWT. Since the AuthInterceptor adds the Bearer token automatically, this should work as long as the user is logged in.

So the API call should be:
```kotlin
@GET("discovery/collections")
suspend fun getDiscoveryCollections(): DiscoveryCollectionsResponse
```
(No admin secret header ‚Äî let the AuthInterceptor add JWT automatically)

BUT if AuthInterceptor doesn't exist or doesn't add Bearer tokens, add the admin secret as a fallback. Check AuthInterceptor.kt first.

3. Add a simple domain model if needed, or just use the DTO directly in the UI layer since collections are transient (not persisted in Room).

Must compile successfully.

Add a 'Featured Collections' section to the Discovery screen showing 6 collection cards in a grid layout.

Changes to DiscoveryViewModel.kt:
1. Add state: `private val _collections = MutableStateFlow<List<DiscoveryCollectionDto>>(emptyList())`
2. Add `val collections: StateFlow<List<DiscoveryCollectionDto>> = _collections.asStateFlow()`
3. Add `private val _isLoadingCollections = MutableStateFlow(false)`
4. In `loadData()`, add a launch block to fetch collections:
```kotlin
launch {
    try {
        _isLoadingCollections.value = true
        val response = api.getDiscoveryCollections()
        if (response.success) {
            _collections.value = response.data.collections
        }
    } catch (e: Exception) {
        // Collections are optional, don't show error
    } finally {
        _isLoadingCollections.value = false
    }
}
```
Note: You'll need to inject VettrApi into the ViewModel (it may already be available through StockRepository or directly).

Changes to DiscoveryScreen.kt:
1. Collect collections state: `val collections by viewModel.collections.collectAsStateWithLifecycle()`
2. Add Featured Collections section ABOVE Featured Stocks in the LazyColumn
3. Use a 2-column grid layout with LazyVerticalGrid or manual Column+Row arrangement:

Collection Card composable (`CollectionCard`):
```kotlin
@Composable
fun CollectionCard(
    collection: DiscoveryCollectionDto,
    onClick: () -> Unit,
    modifier: Modifier = Modifier
) {
    Column(
        modifier = modifier
            .cardStyle()
            .clickable(onClick = onClick)
            .vettrPadding(),
        verticalArrangement = Arrangement.spacedBy(Spacing.sm)
    ) {
        // Icon in circle
        Box(
            modifier = Modifier
                .size(36.dp)
                .clip(CircleShape)
                .background(VettrAccent.copy(alpha = 0.15f)),
            contentAlignment = Alignment.Center
        ) {
            Text(
                text = iconToEmoji(collection.icon),
                style = MaterialTheme.typography.titleMedium
            )
        }
        // Title
        Text(
            text = collection.name,
            style = MaterialTheme.typography.titleSmall,
            fontWeight = FontWeight.Bold,
            maxLines = 1,
            overflow = TextOverflow.Ellipsis
        )
        // Tagline
        Text(
            text = collection.tagline,
            style = MaterialTheme.typography.bodySmall,
            color = MaterialTheme.colorScheme.onSurfaceVariant,
            maxLines = 2,
            overflow = TextOverflow.Ellipsis
        )
        // Criteria summary
        Text(
            text = collection.criteriaSummary,
            style = MaterialTheme.typography.labelSmall,
            color = VettrAccent,
            fontWeight = FontWeight.Medium
        )
    }
}
```

