Grid layout ‚Äî render 2 cards per row:
```kotlin
item {
    Column(verticalArrangement = Arrangement.spacedBy(Spacing.md)) {
        SectionHeader(title = "Featured Collections")
        collections.chunked(2).forEach { row ->
            Row(
                horizontalArrangement = Arrangement.spacedBy(Spacing.md),
                modifier = Modifier.fillMaxWidth()
            ) {
                row.forEach { collection ->
                    CollectionCard(
                        collection = collection,
                        onClick = { /* navigate to detail */ },
                        modifier = Modifier.weight(1f)
                    )
                }
                // Add spacer if odd number
                if (row.size == 1) {
                    Spacer(modifier = Modifier.weight(1f))
                }
            }
        }
    }
}
```

For the collection detail view, when a user clicks a collection card, navigate to a new CollectionDetailScreen. For now, clicking a card can show a bottom sheet or a simple navigation ‚Äî OR just pass the collection data via nav args.

Simplest approach: Add `onCollectionClick: (String) -> Unit = {}` callback to DiscoveryScreen params, and the caller can handle navigation.

Skeleton: Show 6 skeleton cards (2x3 grid) while loading collections.

Must compile successfully.

Create a Collection Detail screen that shows all stocks in a selected collection.

Create new file: `app/src/main/java/com/vettr/android/feature/discovery/CollectionDetailScreen.kt`

The screen receives collection data (either via navigation args or by re-fetching collections and finding by ID).

Simplest approach: Pass the collection ID as a nav arg, fetch collections in the screen's ViewModel, and find the matching collection.

Option A (preferred for simplicity): Create a simple composable that receives a `DiscoveryCollectionDto` directly and just displays it. The parent (DiscoveryScreen or NavHost) passes the data.

Option B: Create a CollectionDetailViewModel that fetches collections and filters by ID.

Go with Option A ‚Äî create the composable and wire it up.

```kotlin
@Composable
fun CollectionDetailScreen(
    collection: DiscoveryCollectionDto,
    onBackClick: () -> Unit,
    onStockClick: (String) -> Unit,
    modifier: Modifier = Modifier
) {
    Scaffold(
        topBar = {
            // Simple top bar with back button and collection name
        }
    ) { padding ->
        LazyColumn(
            modifier = modifier.padding(padding).padding(Spacing.md),
            verticalArrangement = Arrangement.spacedBy(Spacing.md)
        ) {
            // Header with icon, name, tagline
            item {
                CollectionHeader(collection)
            }

            // Stock list
            items(collection.stocks, key = { it.ticker }) { stock ->
                CollectionStockRow(
                    stock = stock,
                    onClick = { /* find stock ID and navigate */ }
                )
            }
        }
    }
}
```

CollectionStockRow should show:
- Ticker (bold, accent color)
- Company name
- Sector chip
- Price
- Price change (green/red)
- VETR score badge

For navigation integration: Since this is a simple screen, you can either:
1. Use a dialog/bottom sheet from DiscoveryScreen (simplest)
2. OR add a new composable destination in VettrNavHost

Go with approach 1 for simplicity: Show the detail in a full-screen dialog or a dedicated composable that replaces the content.

Alternative simpler approach: In DiscoveryScreen, when a collection card is clicked, show the collection detail inline using a state variable:
```kotlin
var selectedCollection by remember { mutableStateOf<DiscoveryCollectionDto?>(null) }

if (selectedCollection != null) {
    CollectionDetailScreen(
        collection = selectedCollection!!,
        onBackClick = { selectedCollection = null },
        onStockClick = onStockClick
    )
} else {
    // ... existing discovery content
}
```

This avoids modifying VettrNavHost.kt and keeps things contained.

Must compile successfully.
